Module 1: Communication in a Connected World
1.1 Network Types
1.1.2 Everything is Online
We expect our devices (phones, tablets, laptops, desktops) to always be connected to the internet.
We use networks to interact with friends, shop, share pictures/experiences, and learn.
The internet is usually thought of as a "place" to find or share information, not as physical connections.
1.1.3 Who Owns "The Internet"?
The internet is not owned by any individual or group.
It is a worldwide collection of interconnected networks (an "internetwork"), cooperating using common standards.
Connections happen through telephone wires, fiber-optic cables, wireless transmissions, and satellite links.
Everything accessed online (social media, games, email, online courses) is connected to local networks that send/receive info through the internet.
Examples of how networks connect the world:
Intelligent networks let handheld devices receive news/emails and send texts.
Video conferencing connects people around the globe instantly.
Phones share voice, text, and images globally.
Online gaming connects thousands of people seamlessly.
1.1.4 Local Networks
Networks range from 2 computers to hundreds of thousands of devices.
SOHO (Small Office/Home Office) networks – let a few local users share resources (printers, documents, pictures, music).
Businesses use large networks to advertise/sell products, order supplies, and communicate with customers.
Network communication (email, instant messaging) is usually more efficient/cheaper than traditional mail or long-distance calls.
The internet is called a "network of networks" because it's made up of thousands of connected local networks.

Types of Networks:

Type	Description
Small Home Networks	Connect a few computers to each other and to the internet
SOHO Networks	Allow home/remote office computers to connect to a corporate network or shared resources
Medium to Large Networks	Used by corporations/schools; many locations, hundreds/thousands of hosts
World Wide Networks	The internet itself — connects hundreds of millions of computers worldwide
