1.2 Data Transmission
1.2.2 The Bit
Computers and networks work only with binary digits (bits) — 0 or 1.
A bit ("binary digit") is the smallest piece of data; humans interpret words/pictures, computers interpret bit patterns.
A bit is stored/transmitted as one of two discrete states (e.g., two voltage levels, two light intensities, magnetization directions, on/off).
Input devices (mouse, keyboard, mic) translate human interaction → binary for the CPU.
Output devices (printer, speakers, monitor) translate binary → human-recognizable form.
ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange): each character = 8 bits.
A = 01000001
9 = 00111001
= 00100011
A group of 8 bits = 1 byte.
Codes can represent almost any digital info: data, graphics, photos, voice, video, music.
1.2.3 Common Methods of Data Transmission
After data becomes bits, it's converted into signals sent across network media (copper wire, fiber-optic cable, electromagnetic waves/air).
A signal = electrical/optical pattern transmitted from one device to another, representing bits as pulses of electricity, pulses of light, or radio waves.
Signals may convert multiple times as media changes along the path.

Three common transmission methods:

Method	Description
Electrical signals	Data represented as electrical pulses on copper wire
Optical signals	Electrical signals converted into light pulses
Wireless signals	Infrared, microwave, or radio waves through the air
Homes/small businesses: mostly copper cables or Wi-Fi.
Larger networks: fiber-optic cables for reliable, long-distance signal transmission.
1.2.4 Check Your Understanding – Answers
Bit – basic unit of information representing one of two discrete states.
Inferred data – data (like location/preferences) that a company learns about you based on your activity (e.g., credit card purchases).
Optical signals – use frequencies or pulses of light.
1.3 Bandwidth and Throughput
1.3.1 Bandwidth
Bandwidth is the capacity of a medium (network connection) to carry data — essentially, how much data can be transmitted over a given period of time.
Usually measured in bits per second (bps), and commonly seen as kbps, Mbps, or Gbps.
Bandwidth is determined by both the physical properties of the media (e.g., copper, fiber, wireless) and the technologies used to transmit signals.
Bandwidth is a theoretical/rated maximum — actual data transfer speed (throughput) is often lower.
1.3.2 Throughput
Throughput = the actual measure of the transfer of bits across media over a given time period.
Throughput usually does not match the specified bandwidth due to several factors:
Amount of data being sent/received.
Types of data being transmitted.
Latency – time (including delays) for data to travel from one point to another, caused by number of network devices in the path.
Throughput measurements don't account for whether the bits are "useful" — includes network control messages (traffic regulation, error correction), not just user data.
In an internetwork with multiple segments, throughput cannot exceed the slowest link in the path — even one low-bandwidth segment slows the whole path.
Online speed tests can measure a connection's throughput.
1.3.4 Check Your Understanding – Answers
Bandwidth – capacity of the medium to carry data.
Throughput – measurement that includes latency encountered during transmission.
Bits per second (bps) – standard unit that reflects throughput/latency-inclusive measurement.
